<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900423-0097</DOCNO><DOCID>900423-0097.</DOCID><HL>   South Africa's Trade Surplus</HL><DATE>04/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A</SO><CO>   AFRIC</CO><IN>MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><LP>   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- South Africa's trade surplusnarrowed to 1.17 billion rand ($442.8 million) in March fromsurpluses of 1.79 billion rand a year earlier and 1.77billion rand in February, the Customs and Excise office said.   The figures aren't seasonally adjusted, but export andimport data are adjusted to bring them in line withrequirements for compiling the nation's balance of payments.Exports in March fell to 4.49 billion rand from 5.22 billionrand a year earlier, and imports declined to 3.33 billionrand from 3.44 billion rand.</LP><TEXT>   In the first quarter, exports grew to 14.42 billion randfrom 12.92 billion rand a year earlier, and imports increasedto 10.38 billion rand from 9.99 billion rand.   The trade figures include South Africa's exports of goldbullion, its principal source of foreign exchange earnings.Imports include the country's purchases of oil and otherpetroleum products, despite the longstanding embargo of theOrganization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.</TEXT></DOC>